"full_text": "Radiology\nImaging of traumatic and non-\ntraumatic GIT emergencies\nTraumatic Non-Traumatic\nBlunt trauma 1. The most common\ncause is:\n1. RTA\n2. itis (inflammation)\n2. Falling from height\n3. Assaults\n4. Sports\nPenetrating trauma\n1. Stab\n2. Gun shot\nTraumatic GIT emergencies Imaging modalities\nUltrasonography\nUsed at the time of primary survey, to detect free fluid with the abdominal or pleural\nspace (may be due to bleeding or bowel perforation), cardiac hemopericardium.\nAdvantage: Fast Does not expose the patient to ionizing radiation.\nLimitations: depends on operator skill and patient factors such as bowel gas and\nobesity.\nGood at detecting free abdominal fluid, but cannot out rule bleeding or organ\ndamage (good positive but not a good negative test)\nThis is called a Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma (FAST) scan.\n92"}